            , and saw her at the Keys at 12 at Noon that Day very bad. Ann Trundley confirmed the former Evidence; and being askt whether she knew 
               <persName id="t17201012-37-person252">
                  Ann 
                  Pooley 
               <interp inst="t17201012-37-person252" type="surname" value="Pooley"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17201012-37-person252" type="given" value="Ann"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17201012-37-person252" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , and what was become of her, said, Yes, she went into the Country, got in Ague, and Fever, and came up and died with a Parish Nurse on Tower-Hill; that she used to be with them, but was not there that Night. The 4 first Evidences being call'd again, deposed, that they did not see either of those two Girls there; but that it was the Deceased that they saw the Prisoner kick. The Prisoner called several Gentlemen of great Reputation and Worth to his Credit, who gave him a very good Character, and that he was a Man of Compassion and not of Cruelty. The Jury considering the whole matter, <rs id="t17201012-37-verdict209" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t17201012-37-verdict209" type="verdictCategory" value="notGuilty"></interp>
               acquitted
            </rs> him.</p>
